<!-- By Dependent Issues (Action) - DO NOT REMOVE -->

This file should be easy to PR separately.

In general I think these `Equiv`s should be obtained by combining both directions (`RingHom`s in this case). We should show that `AddMonoidAlgebra ¬∑ G` is a functor (prove the `comp` and `id` lemmas) and deduce that both directions are inverse to each other.

Some assumptions might be able to be generalized, e.g. here [AddZeroClass G] should work.

```suggestion
  simp_rw [Finsupp.indicator_eq_sum_single, sum_mul, mul_sum,
```
I think these can be removed now (more general versions were merged)

This seems to be the only place `minpoly.eq_of_algHom_eq` is used. Should be easy to use [minpoly.minpoly_algHom](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/FieldTheory/Minpoly/Basic.html#minpoly.minpoly_algHom) instead?

```suggestion
  carrier := {x | ‚àÄ f : Gal s, AddMonoidAlgebra.mapDomainAlgAut ‚Ñö _ f.toAddEquiv x = x}
```
This is supposed to be a set

`iterate_derivative_X_add_pow`, `iterate_derivative_X_sub_pow`, `coeff_iterate_derivative_as_prod_range` are not used anywhere, so I guess we could just change their statements?

I haven't looked at Derivative2.lean carefully, but some stuff there look like they could be PR'd into this file ...

I plan to use a proof similar to [Algebra.IsAlgebraic.range_eval_eq_rootSet_minpoly](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/blob/193761250a9869327056b499a7f49d676ed5e3a9/Mathlib/FieldTheory/IsAlgClosed/Basic.lean#L561-L580) which should be shorter and avoids the HEq stuff, but it would require manually filling some instance arguments, because we want two different maps from `F[X]/c.minpoly = F[X]/d.minpoly` to `E` ... and this lemma can be moved near [AlgHom.liftNormal](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/FieldTheory/Normal.html#AlgHom.liftNormal).

I also think it may be better to use the equivalence relation `minpoly c = minpoly d` to define `GalConjClasses`, which is more "invariant", as it doesn't depend on which (even non-normal over F) field `c` and `d` lie in, so if you have an injective `E`-AlgHom `f` then `c ~ d` implies `f c ~ f d`. Then, this lemma would show the new definition is equivalent to the current definition (via Galois group action) when F/E is normal.

[MvPolynomial.symmetricSubalgebra](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/RingTheory/MvPolynomial/Symmetric.html#MvPolynomial.symmetricSubalgebra) and this are both special cases of the same construction: a set of `AddMonoidHom`s from a monoid/AddZeroClass `A` to itself, which induces `AlgHom`s from `F[A]` to itself, and we take the subalgebra invariant under all these `AlgHom`s. In the case of `MvPolynomial.symmetricSubalgebra`, the `AddMonoidHom`s from `A := œÉ ‚Üí‚ÇÄ ‚Ñï` to itself comes from permutations `œÉ ‚âÉ œÉ`, and here they come from `AlgEquiv`s from `A := K s` to itself which are in particular `AddMonoidHom`s.

When these `AddMonoidHom`s form a group (and therefore are `AddMonoidEquiv`s), `A` is partitioned into orbits of this group action, and an element in `x : F[A]` is in this subalgebra iff `x a = x b` whenever `a` and `b` are in the same orbit.

The LHS can be replaced by the subset of `A ‚Üí‚ÇÄ F` consisting of elements `x` such that `x a = x b` whenever `a ~ b` for some equivalence relation `~` on `A`, and `GalConjClasses ‚Ñö (K s)` would be replaced by the quotient by the equivalence relation. This works for `Pi` always, but for `Finsupp` the right-to-left direction needs the equivalence classes to be finite.

The next 150+ lines seem to be mainly using this `Equiv` (and the strengthened `toConjLinearEquiv` which doesn't require any additional instances on the RHS.) to transfer algebraic instances on the LHS to the RHS, and it's not yet clear to me why this is necessary; could we not just use this Equiv to map to the LHS and do all algebraic operations there?

I think we may as well write this integral
![image](https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/assets/3064145/1e8b4f8e-d355-4a62-a3ac-05fc28901745)
as $s\int_0^1 e^{(1-t)s}f_i(st)\ dt$ with the change of variable $x=st$. Hopefully makes the proofs easier?

I'm wondering whether it would be easier to take the [normalClosure](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/FieldTheory/NormalClosure.html#normalClosure) of `IntermediateField.adjoin ‚Ñö s` in `‚ÑÇ`, or we can do it in one step by adjoining all conjugates (same minpoly) of elements in `s`. Or maybe we can directly work with automorphisms of ‚ÑÇ rather than of an intermediate field?
